#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>*p<0.05</b> - The hypothesis of normal distribution was rejected by the "
"Shapiro-Wilk test"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Alpha (α)</b> is the significance level, representing the maximum "
"acceptable probability of committing a Type I error (detecting a false "
"positive difference when none actually exists)."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Balance</b> - balance between correct and incorrect classified "
"(TP+TN)/(FP+FN)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>BETWEENNESS</b>: number of shortest paths between all pairs of nodes that "
"pass through this node; shows its importance as a \"bridge\" or transit "
"point."
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Calculated parameter</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>CCR</b> - Correct Classification Rate or accuracy of the positive and "
"negative classifications (TP+TN)/(TN+FP+FN+TP)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Centrality metrics</b> (different measures of a node's importance in the "
"network)."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>CLOSENESS</b>: inverse of the sum of shortest path lengths to all other "
"nodes; shows how central a node is in terms of distance."
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Clusters (k1/k2)</b> represent the required number of clusters (e.g., "
"clinics or schools) per group. This is adjusted for similarity among "
"subjects within the same cluster using the Intraclass Correlation "
"Coefficient (<b>ICC</b>) and average cluster size via the Design Effect."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Concordance</b> - C-Statistic or AUC. The probability that a randomly "
"chosen subject with the condition is correctly ranked higher than a randomly "
"chosen subject without the condition"
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid "<b>Correlation method</b>: {method}"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Design</b>:"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: Cohen's d"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: Cohen's w"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: correlation coefficient (r)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: Eta-squared (η²)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: Hazard Ratio (HR)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: Odds Ratio"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid "<b>Effect size measure</b>: R-squared change (f²)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Effect Size</b> measures the standardized magnitude of the difference or "
"association (e.g., Cohen's d for means, or correlation coefficient). Unlike "
"p-values, it is independent of the sample size."
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Events (N1)</b> represents the required number of target events (e.g., "
"deaths or failures) to achieve the desired power. In survival analysis, "
"statistical power is driven by the number of events rather than the total "
"number of subjects."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>EXPECTED INFLUENCE</b>: sum of signed weights of connected edges; shows "
"the node's net impact on the network, considering positive and negative "
"relations."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Explanatory</b> - variable corresponding to MAR with minimal "
"p<sub>value</sub>."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid "<b>Hₐ</b> is negative correlation"
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid "<b>Hₐ</b> is positive correlation"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Hazard Ratio (HR)</b> represents the ratio of event rates between the two "
"groups. A Hazard Ratio of 1 indicates no difference in risk, while values "
"further from 1 represent stronger effects."
msgstr ""

#: R/msrv.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Hazard Ratio (HR)</b> represents the ratio of the hazard rates "
"corresponding to the conditions described by two levels of an explanatory "
"variable (Cox, 1972). It indicates the relative risk of event occurrence per "
"unit change in the predictor. An <b>HR > 1</b> indicates an increased hazard "
"(higher risk of the event), while an <b>HR < 1</b> indicates a decreased "
"hazard (protective effect). <b>Lower/Upper 95% CI</b> represent the "
"confidence interval for the Hazard Ratio."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmlp.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Hidden Layers</b>: network architecture (hidden layer sizes, hidden / "
"output activation functions)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mmlp.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Hold-out Accuracy</b>: classification accuracy on the hold-out validation "
"dataset."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmlp.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>K-Fold CV Accuracy</b>: average classification accuracy across "
"cross-validation folds."
msgstr ""

#: R/msrv.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Kaplan-Meier estimator</b> (Kaplan & Meier, 1958) is a non-parametric "
"statistic used to estimate the survival function from lifetime data, "
"accounting for censored observations. <b>Median survival</b> is the "
"estimated time at which 50% of the subjects have experienced the event "
"(survival probability drops to 0.5). <b>Lower/Upper 95% CI</b> represent the "
"95% confidence interval limits for this median survival time."
msgstr ""

#: R/msrv.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Likelihood Ratio</b>, <b>Wald</b>, and <b>Score (Log-rank)</b> tests "
"assess the global null hypothesis that all regression coefficients (beta) in "
"the model are equal to zero. Statistically significant p-values (p < 0.05) "
"indicate that the predictors collectively improve the model fit relative to "
"a null model without covariates."
msgstr ""

#: R/msrv.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Log-rank (Mantel-Cox) test</b> is a non-parametric hypothesis test that "
"compares the survival distributions of two or more independent groups. It "
"evaluates the null hypothesis that there is no difference in survival curves "
"between groups. <b>Chi-square</b> is the test statistic based on observed "
"vs. expected events, and the <b>p-value</b> indicates the statistical "
"significance of the differences under the null hypothesis."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>LR-</b> - Negative Likelihood Ratio P(-|D+))/(P(-|D-)). The probability "
"of a person with the condition receiving a negative classification / "
"probability of a person without the condition receiving a negative "
"classification"
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>LR+</b> - Positive Likelihood Ratio (P(+|D+))/(P(+|D-)) The probability "
"of a person with the condition receiving a positive classification / "
"probability of a person without the condition receiving a positive "
"classification"
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>MAR</b> - missing at random (if each p<sub>value</sub> is significant, "
"there is evidence the data is MAR);"
msgstr ""

#: R/mmlp.b.R
msgid "<b>Max Iterations</b>: maximum number of training epochs."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>MCAR</b> - missing completely at random (if the p<sub>value</sub> is not "
"significant, there is evidence the data is MCAR)."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Method</b>: Classical Partial Correlation (no regularization/L1 penalty). "
"Computes the linear association between each pair of variables while "
"controlling for all other variables in the dataset, producing a fully "
"connected network."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Method</b>: Classical Semi-Partial Correlation (no regularization/L1 "
"penalty). Computes the linear association between each pair of variables "
"while controlling for all other variables in the dataset from only the "
"second variable, yielding an asymmetric network."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Method</b>: Graphical Lasso (GLASSO) with a manual penalty parameter (rho "
"= {rho}). GLASSO uses L1 regularization to shrink weak partial correlations "
"to exactly zero, producing a sparse network."
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Method</b>: Graphical Lasso (GLASSO) with Extended Bayesian Information "
"Criterion (EBIC) tuning parameter selection (gamma = {gamma}). GLASSO uses "
"L1 regularization to shrink weak partial correlations to exactly zero, "
"producing a sparse network."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>More Certain Interval (MCI)</b> is interval outside the Uncertain "
"Interval and divide into low and high parts."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid "<b>MSE</b> - mean squared error (for Continuous variables);"
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid "<b>N</b> - number of missing values;"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>N1</b> and <b>N2</b> represent the required number of subjects in Group 1 "
"and Group 2. The ratio of their sizes is determined by the specified "
"allocation ratio."
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>N1</b> represents the required sample size (total number of subjects in "
"the single group, or total number of pairs for paired comparisons)."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid "<b>NPV</b> - Negative Predictive Value of the negative class TN/(TN+FN)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>PFC</b> - proportion of falsely classified (for Nominal and Ordinal "
"variables);"
msgstr ""

#: R/mpwr.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Power</b> is the probability of correctly detecting a statistically "
"significant difference when a true difference exists in the population (1 - "
"Type II error rate, or the probability of avoiding a false negative)."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid "<b>PPV</b> - Positive Predictive Value of the positive class TP/(TN+FN)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>PVU</b> - proportion of variance unexplained 1-R² (for Continuous "
"variables);"
msgstr ""

#: R/msrv.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Schoenfeld residuals test</b> evaluates the proportional hazards (PH) "
"assumption of the Cox model for each covariate individually and globally. It "
"tests whether the effect of the covariates is constant over time. A "
"statistically significant <b>p-value (p < 0.05)</b> indicates a violation of "
"the PH assumption, meaning the hazard ratio changes over time."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Se</b> - sensitivity of the positive and negative classifications "
"TP/(TP+FN)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid "<b>SNPV</b> - standardized negative predictive value of the negative class"
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Sp</b> - specificity of the positive and negative classifications "
"TN/(TN+FN)"
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid "<b>SPPV</b> - standardized positive predictive value of the positive class"
msgstr ""

#: R/mcor.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>STRENGTH</b>: sum of absolute weights of connected edges; shows how "
"strongly a node is directly connected to its neighbors."
msgstr ""

#: R/msrv.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Time-dependent ROC</b> analysis (Heagerty et al., 2000) evaluates the "
"predictive accuracy of continuous markers for time-to-event outcomes at a "
"specific time point <i>t</i>, classifying patients into event-occurring or "
"event-free states. <b>AUC</b> (Area Under the Curve) measures the "
"discriminative ability (ranging from 0.5 to 1.0). <b>Cut-off</b> represents "
"the optimal threshold determined by the Youden index (J = Sensitivity + "
"Specificity - 1)."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmlp.b.R
msgid "<b>Training Accuracy</b>: classification accuracy on the training dataset."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Uncertain Interval (UI)</b> is placed around the point of intersection "
"between the two distributions with and without the targeted state."
msgstr ""

#: R/mui.b.R
msgid ""
"<b>Uncertain Interval</b> is considered to be a range of test scores that is "
"inconclusive and does not warrant a right decision."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmlp.b.R
msgid "<b>Weight Decay</b>: L2 regularization penalty parameter."
msgstr ""

#: R/mmf.b.R
msgid "<h2>Help</h2><div>Please select complete and incomplete variables</div>"
msgstr "<h2>Pomoć</h2><div>Odaberi potpune i nepotpune varijable</div>"

